<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Theater Critic<ep>
   Though its Tony Awards are a half-century old this year, Broadway cast a vote for youth and exuberance on Monday when the Pulitzer Prize-winning <m0>Rent <m0>and the ode-to-tap musical <m0>Bring in 'Da Noise, Bring in 'Da Funk <m0>got 10 and nine nominations respectively to lead all shows in the race for the 50th annual Tonys.<ep>
   The awards, which will be presented June 2 from 9 to 11 a.m. on CBS (channels 4 and 12) in ceremonies hosted by nominee Nathan Lane, pit <m0>Rent <m0>(by 35-year-old Jonathan Larson, who died the night before the lionized show's first preview Off-Broadway) against <m0>Noise/Funk <m0>(a musical that <m1> <m0>didn't even exist on its first day of rehearsal at Off-Broadway's Public Theater last August) in five categories: <m1> <m0>best musical, best book, best score, best actor in a musical and best lighting design.<ep>
   The deeper question, of course, is whether hidebound Broadway will actually give these noisy, revitalizing, transferred-from-downtown upstarts awards as well as nominations. <m1> <m0>Though it's true that the Tonys are reaching out to younger theater fans with a World Wide Web site (<m0>http://www.tonys.org<m0>), the awards themselves are voted on by 720 theater folk and journalists, many of whom are older (--) way, way older (--) than the target audiences for <m0>Rent <m0>and <m0>Noise/Funk<m0>.<ep>
