   The Steppenwolf Theater production of Sam Shepard's <m0>Buried Child <m0>(--) winner of 1979's drama Pulitzer (--) was substantially rewritten by Shepard and is up for the best play Tony and four others; in fact, it was done Off-Broadway in 1978, and the new version represents Shepard's Broadway debut. <m1> <m0>Its strongest competition is from Terrence McNally's <m0>Master Class<m0>, followed by August Wilson's <m0>Seven Guitars <m0>(which led all plays with eight nominations) and David Hare's now-closed <m0>Racing Demon<m0>.<ep>
 <m1><styl>cxoff<ql>
<m0>  The Lincoln Center Theater production of Edward Albee's 1966 Pulitzer-winning <m0>A Delicate Balance<m0>, with seven nominations, is the hot contender for best revival of a play. <m1> <m0>Two British productions (--) the Peter Hall-directed <m0>An Ideal Husband <m0>and the Royal Shakespeare Company's <m0>A Midsummer Night's Dream <m0>(--) as well as the National Actors Theatre's heralded <m0>Inherit the Wind <m0>are also nominated.<ep>
   Despite the glowing reviews for <m0>A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum<m0>, that musical revival got just four nominations (including the one predicted for star Nathan Lane before the show ever opened) vs. eight for the sumptuous revival of <m0>The King and I<m0>. <m1> <m0>Their competition, long since vanished from Broadway, is <m0>Company <m0>and <m0>Hello, Dolly!<m0><ep>
   Hot individual contenders are <m0>Victor/Victoria <m0>star Julie Andrews, who has never won a Tony but is widely considered a lock for best actress in a musical; Savion Glover, up for best actor in a musical but the likely winner of the best choreographer Tony (since the best actor honor has been all but given to Lane); and Zoe Caldwell, a best actress in a play nominee for her mesmerizing Maria Callas in <m0>Master Class<m0>.<ep>
